With the shorter carbine gas system and the increased gas port pressure, the carbine cycled faster, and at times the cycle rate could be faster than the magazine would feed ammunition. One of the modifications done to increase reliable feeding included enhancing the angle and the length of the feed ramps. This USGI modification was done to both the barrel extension and the upper receiver, creating a longer and steeper feed ramp. These Mil-Spec M4 feed ramps are part of the original CNC manufacturing process. As a result, the factory machined M4 feed ramps on the receiver are hard coat anodized which adds significant strength to the aluminum. This Mil-Spec grade steel gets its’ additional strength and rigidity from an increase in carbon and/or vanadium in the alloy. This will offer increased barrel life and performance through use in all types of extreme environments and temperatures.Chrome Bore and ChamberOne of the first modifications that were made to the original M16 in the mid 1960’s was the addition of the chrome lined bore and chamber. It is now a worldwide standard in the industry for a battle rifle. The chrome bore and chamber is harder than the barrel steel and on the USGI M16/M4 rifles will aid in chambering, extraction, and reliability. It increases velocity, and also resist against fouling and corrosion from extended use in the field. This gives the end user a longer barrel life with less required time in maintenance and cleaning.Manganese Phosphate Barrel Finish Barrels are parkerized with the manganese phosphate finish (Mil-Spec A-A-59267). Military specifications also state that the entire barrel surface is phosphate finished to create a porous surface to absorb oil as to resist against corrosion from the elements. title: For Sale:  Cornell Fire Arms Company 12ga
postcontent:
For sale us a Cornell Fire Arms Company 12ga shotgun.Price is OBO. ~~~
Cornell Firearms Company is a trade name used by Hopkins and Allen Arms Company on hammerless shotguns made under designs marketed formerly by Forehand Arms Company. Hopkins and Allen purchased Forehand Arms Company in 1902 and continued to produce Forehand models until H & A went bankrupt in 1916. There are no records to give an exact date of manufacture.
Although this gun has fluid steel barrels, it was manufactured with the technology of 1900. Additionally, shotgun chambers of this era were often shorter than today's 2 3/4" shells. If shooting is contemplated, and evaluation by a competent gunsmith to determine barrel condition and chamber length is recommended. Firing a 2 3/4" shell in a short chamber creates dangerously high pressures that could damage the gun and injure the shooter and bystanders.
If deemed safe to use, only light field and target loads can be recommended. Under no circumstances should a 3" Magnum shell be fired in this gun, even though it will fit in the chamber.

title: For Sale:  Mosin 91/30 1943 SUPERB WOOD Complete Set Bayo/Sling+ EXC
postcontent: This is a beautiful example of a 1943 Mosin Nagant 91/30 that is a complete set just as they were usually sold. This one stands out for the gorgeous wood though it also has excellent metal finishes as well. Made in 1943, it has all numbers matching that I can see. Ending in 3837, it is on the buttplate, receiver and the magazine/trigger assembly on the bottom. WOOD-- The wood is a laminate type stock I believe with a glossy finish. There is an amazing mix of darker brown, medium tones and golden blonde in the swirls and pattern. The top and bottom edge of the butt and the bottom of the barrel have many parallel lines in the wood, while the sides have center rings and outer ones that swirl and curve. The sides of the butt and beneath the receiver are the best. There are some light and minor scuffs just in front of the barrel bands from sliding them off as they would scrape the wood some. These are minor. METAL-- The metal finish is EXC with the front barrel an even dark finish with no marks from the bayonet. Even the sight hood, cleaning rod and barrel bands have an excellent finish. The receiver has a matte finish with less gloss than the rest and the import stamp is electro-penciled as most recent imports are. The buttplate is the finest bluing as it is glossy and blue and in fantastic condition. BORE/ACTION-- The bore rates a Good+ though in the world of Mosins it is likely a step or so higher as many are not so great. The rifling is all sharp with deep grooves which is the most important part and in the grooves is where you find areas that are not shiny and smooth. To be fair, I have NOT cleaned this bore with a metal brush and have only used paper and cotton patches. It could VERY WELL clean up to EXC as it very nice rifling and a tight bore. ACCESSORIES-- Comes with the dog-collar sling in EXC+ condition, a never used bayonet with a perfect finish and untouched point. Could easily be unused/unissued. Also has the double pouch and then the tools and cleaning items. What is included is in the photos. SHIPPING-- This will ship as a 12 pound box 50+ inches long from 33324. Either Fedex Ground or USPS Priority are the same $42.95. If you live in the Southeast, Fedex will be lower and I will refund the difference. PAYMENT-- For Paypal, you must use "SEND MONEY TO FAMILY AND FRIENDS" to avoid fees and please let me know BEFORE paying as my Paypal address is different than the one used here. LOCAL SALES are fine with proper IDMANY MORE PHOTOS AVAILABLE

title: For Sale:  Mean Arms AR Conversion, CA Compliance
postcontent: To be clear, this is not a firearm. It is a part to convert a standard AR-15 to be CA compliant, which permanently attaches the magazine to the AR. The MA Lock, actually breaks off inside the mag release button after installation so it cannot be removed without an extractor. The MA Loader is a special magazine that allows you to reload the gun through the ejection port, the gun cannot fire until it is removed. Accordingly by having a fixed magazine, you are allowed to keep your features, pistol grip, adjustable stock, flash hider. So I have two sets of, 1 MA Loader and 1 MA Lock, asking $60 per set, they are brand new in the packaging. When I originally bought these, it took 6 months to get them, they are still on backorder due to the huge demand. During that time, I went ahead and converted to featureless. My loss your gain.Too see them in action,https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h69CU84eDl4
